'''Dalal Street''' ({{lang-hi|दलाल पथ}}, {{lang-gu|દલાલ સ્ટ્રીટ}}) in downtown [[Mumbai]], [[India]], is the address of the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]] (in the [[Phiroze Jeejeebhoy Towers]]) and several related financial firms and institutions. When Bombay Stock Exchange was moved to this new location at the intersection of [[Bombay Samachar|Bombay Samāchār]] Marg and Hammam Street, the street next to the building was renamed as ''Dalal Street''{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}. The [[Marathi language|Marathi]] word ''{{transl|mr|dalāl}}'' means "a [[broker]]", "a go-between".<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press| isbn = 978-0-19-864317-3| last = McGregor| first = R. S.| title = Oxford Hindi-English dictionary| location = Oxford| date = 1993}}</ref> Similar to [[Wall Street]] in [[New York City|the New York City]], it is often used as a [[metonym]] for the entire Indian financial industry.

