{{other people|William Baxter}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
'''William Baxter''' (4 December 1911 – 20 April 1979) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, building contractor and farmer.

He was a [[conscientious objector]] in the [[Second World War]].

Having served as a councillor, he was [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Stirlingshire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Stirlingshire]] from [[United Kingdom general election, 1959|1959]] until he stood down at the [[United Kingdom general election, October 1974|October 1974 general election]].

He was asked to stand down by his [[Constituency Labour Party]] after the indecisive [[United Kingdom general election, February 1974|election of February 1974]], when he appeared on television calling for an all-party government of national unity, and suggested that the [[Duke of Edinburgh]] could chair its meetings.

In 1961, as a protest against [[bipartisan]] support for British [[nuclear weapons]], he voted against the [[Royal Air Force]], [[Royal Navy]], and [[British Army]] Estimates in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], and was suspended from the Labour [[Party Whip]] from March 1961 until May 1963.

Baxter received an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate]] from [[Heriot-Watt University]] in 1976 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.hw.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-graduates.htm|title=Heriot-Watt University Edinburgh: Honorary Graduates|last=webperson@hw.ac.uk|website=www1.hw.ac.uk|access-date=2016-04-06}}</ref>

